{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes to TN, but frame as connection not warning",
    "content": "Yes to a TN, but frame it as a *connection*, not a warning.\n\nA philosophically literate English reader encountering \"category theory\" in a philosophical text will almost certainly think of Kant first and wonder whether the author means Kantian categories. A mathematically literate reader will not be confused at all. The TN serves the former without patronizing the latter.\n\nBut \"not to be confused with\" is the wrong framing. The author says the overlap is *intentional*. So the TN should highlight the resonance rather than block it:\n\nSomething like: \"范畴论 (category theory): the mathematical discipline, not Kant's table of categories -- though the resonance is not accidental. Just as Kant's categories structure the conditions of possible experience, the author uses mathematical category theory to describe the structure of experiential fields (境).\"\n\nThis orients the philosophical reader, respects the mathematical reader, and flags the intentional overlap in one sentence."
  }
}
